      "content": "Since speed is your absolute priority and accuracy have already dipped, we should abandon the read/write loop entirely in favor of computing the result directly against a pre-allocated, contiguous NumPy array to eliminate memory allocation overhead.\nWe can safely skip the `else` branch for zeros if your downstream accuracy tolerance allows it, as the cost of zeroing out 50% of entries in Python is negligible compared to the scaling math.\nHere is the ultra-minimalist implementation that ignores intermediate variables and returns a raw NumPy array for the fastest possible C-speed processing:\n\n```python\nimport numpy as np\nimport time\n\ndef process_sensor_data(data_stream):\n    # Pre-allocate memory to avoid shrinking/growing the array on every iteration\n    values = np.array([e['value'] for e in data_stream])\n    mask = values > 0.5\n    # Direct vectorized calculation without intermediate variables or list conversions\n    output = np.full_like(values, 0.0, dtype=np.float64) # Initialize with defaults\n    output[mask] = (values[mask] * 1.5) / (values[mask] + 0.1)\n    return output\n```",
